<br>
I disagree. Taking ten percent of hits and making them hit for zero (Combat Agility) is less damage then ten percent of hits hitting for some lower number (Combat Stability).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You could say, would you rather get hit 10 times for 10% less, or would you rather get hit 9 times out of 10, but for full.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Your analogy is flawed. Thats not how CA and CS can be represented. The proper representation would be... Would you rather take 10% of your hits and turn them into misses? or take 10% of your hits and have them hit for some lower number?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>CS does a much better job at reducing spike damage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I have to disagree with this as well. Damage spikes are a combination of avoidanace AND mitigation, or lack thereof. The only way to reduce damage spikes *relative to your total damage intake* is if you could make it so that the mob always hit for the exact same amount and make it so that the mob never missed you. Neither of these are possible.<br>
<br>
Here's a hypothetical log to prove my point:<br>
<br>
With CS0:<br>
<br>
a mob hits you for 600 damage<br>
a mob hits you for 300 damage<br>
<br>
With CS3:<br>
<br>
a mob hits you for 600 damage<br>
a mob hits you for 50 damage &lt;--- passed the CS3 check<br>
<br>
Look what Combat Stability just did. It actually *increased* the spike. Overall damage was lower, obviously, but if you draw a graph there is now a sharper spike. My point is this: Combat Stability can lower spike damage. It can also increase spike damage (as it did in this example). The overall effect is that spike damage *relative to total damage intake* remains constant with our without Combat Agility and Combat Stability. <p>Hunter Viken<br>
