<br>
CM0:<br>
<br>
a mob hits you for 200 damage<br>
a mob hits you for 550 damage<br>
a mob hits you for 600 damage<br>
a mob hits you for 75 damage<br>
a mob hits you for 300 damage<br>
a mob hits you for 350 damage<br>
<br>
CM3:<br>
<br>
a mob hits you for 50 damage &lt;--- mitigated<br>
a mob hits you for 50 damage &lt;--- mitigated<br>
a mob hits you for 600 damage<br>
a mob hits you for 50 damage &lt;--- mitigated<br>
a mob hits you for 50 damage &lt;--- mitigated<br>
a mob hits you for 50 damage &lt;--- mitigated<br>
<br>
Now, if you can agree that this is how combat stability works (ie: takes some percentage of hits and mitigates them down to DI 1) then you can clearly see how, in this case, CM served to increase the damage spike. If you draw a moving-average graph of damage over time you'll see a MUCH bigger spike with CM3 then with CM0. Again, my point is not that CS increases damage spikes or decreases them. My point is that they dont affect spikes at all. In the long run it remains constant. The only thing we can say for certain is that they decrease damage taken.<br>
<br>
